Dry Dry Dry  While I haven’t been to Greece, I’ve been to the Greek spots in the city and Astoria to compare this to, even street meat fares better.  Given the simplicity of the menu and offerings, I don’t understand how they can’t get it right.  I think their weak spot is sourcing of poor meats, then over cooking it until it is a dry and salty, and then putting it in a dry pita.  One would not use an adjective like succulent, it seems the dryness exacerbated the salt levels, that is not a substitute for flavor.  On top of it all, given a street truck is working with about a six sq ft space, it is incredible to wait as long as one does at Grk.  NYers are accustomed to time based on NY minutes, but as one waits one ponders why an order can take over two minutes to make.  It’s not even a matter of taste based on authentic Greek food, it just doesn’t taste plain good, let alone done right as their tag line states. Taste is subjective and the lunchtime lines would suggest that they’re doing something right, but then again the Ford Taurus was a bestseller, McD selling billions.  There is nothing more upsetting than paying too much for food that takes too long to make, and doesn’t taste good, where two of the four main ingredients are too dry, overcooked and salty.  Waste of time and money, very upsetting experience

My friend and I decided to venture over to GRK on Thursday for lunch. We ordered ahead of time via Ritual so that we wouldn't have to wait in any lines. Although their yeero plates sound good, I wasn't too hungry that day, so I opted for the Aegean slaw (red and green cabbage with carrots, onions and fresh herbs dressed in a lemon vinaigrette), and Chicken Avgolemono (soup made with chicken, chicken broth, rice, egg and lemon juice). The slaw was great. It was light and refreshing, perfect for a hot summer day. The soup was not perfect for a hot summer day (but that's on me). I liked the first half of my soup - definitely something I would eat if I'm sick and don't feel like have a boring, bland chicken noodle soup. However, the more I ate it, the saltier it tasted. Maybe the soup is not one of their popular items. Next time I want a more filling lunch, I wouldn't mind trying one of their plates.

There was a beetle in their food. Yes, a beetle, maybe even many beetles. Don’t go here if you don’t wanna beetle in your food. last week, I ate a black beetle from the frozen yogurt black cherry jam. The beetle was in my mouth and when my teeth felt something, I spit it out. Luckily, the beetle was already dead. I was so disgusted, I went to the restaurant, told the manager what happened and showed him the beetle. He took the beetle, smiled and apologized, offered to give the yogurt money back, but he didn’t give the beetle back. I asked for it three times. He still didn’t until I talked to his supervisor on the phone. Turns out he threw the beetle in the trash. Maybe he thought destroying the evidence would solve everything. In the end, they asked me to leave my contact information and promised to give me a reasonable explanation later. It’s been over a week and no one contacted me. I called the manager and no one picked up. Think about how many hours the jam has been cooked, how many hours the beetle was in there. I’m still disgusted by the beetle, disgusted by the fact that they had a dead beetle in the jam. More disgustingly, it’s their attitude. Their food is not clean. And they refuse to admit it, they refuse to apology.

Great fast food concept.  I described it to a colleague this way - its the "Chipotle" of Greek cuisine.  Pick your protein, your presentation (salad, gyro), your sauce, your sides.  Their soda fountain offers natural colas.  There's a wait at lunch - as this location has been "found" by the large population of office workers.  Yet, the staff here is hard working and keeps it moving.  Generous seating if you want to eat in.  Not too far to City Hall Park if tourist or the World Trade Center or Broadway if you want to eat at your desk.

Better food for cheaper at a halal cart. I walked in feeling like I was in the mood for a gyro. The place is very clean and spacious and it’s hard to make a bad gyro so I decided to give it a try. I ordered the chicken “yeero” with the original tahini and a side of the spicy tahini. It was just so bland. The tahini was too yogurty, as in, not enough flavor. The main flavor was the yogurt. I also ordered a side of seasoned fries and they were seasoned, yeah, but didn’t have any salt in the seasoning at all. So it was just strange. I know flavor, I work in a fine dining restaurant and have been in the restaurant industry for 6 years and this was just a disappointment. It’s bland. I guess if you don’t season your food at home this is the place to go. But it was just so bland. The environment was clean and relaxing, though.
